Children.Name: Energy Management
Children.Description: Ability to establish, organize, optimize, and monitor sources of power for the enterprise.

Comments.Comment: Added during 3/10/17 team workshop (includes fuel).
Example: Truck and jet fuel

SME Frank Rouse (Aircraft MX):  team of 300-400 aircraft mechanics, operate 24/7.  If temperatures exceed 75 degrees, air condition carts are hooked to aircraft to cool and conserve fuel. Carts are the size of a small baggage cart and gasoline powered off a generator. Daily 7am call dictates what actions need to occur. 150 carts total for MEM/ 1 cart per aircraft, except 2 carts for 777. Every gate in MEM has a cart and store extra for preventive maintenance. In MEM we do not heat the aircraft only cool them (Canada utilizes heat for aircraft). Fuel hedging occurs with jet fuel and GOCC will put more fuel on the aircraft.  SME Karra Seskey(GRD Fuel Mgmt):  83 Fuel Islands, contracts with the major oil companies, set up contracts for contractors using vans, tractor trailers, etc provide them with 2 credit card types. 5 Dispatchers located in PITT dispatch utilize the Fuel Quest System. Perform reconciliation daily - Ground sells the fuel and utilizes 'diesel and bio fuel'. Fuel hedging does not occur with diesel.   SME Kim Olivito (GRD Sustainability):  Utilities, Natural Gas and use Third Party vendors. Manage SOLAR in house, we do not own the SOLAR. The SOLAR provider does maintenance on the 'panels, we have an agreed upon rate.- ddj

SME John Rutkauskas (Facility) indicated 2955 Republic bldg has a 'net zero design' and highest rated prototype with SOLAR panels. Sustainability: modify and refurbish old furniture as new and reuse as 'Green practice'. Karen Ellis MD area performs environmental site assessments. James Jenkins area work directly with MLGW to manage FedEx domestic utility consumption.

Children.Name: Human Resource Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a Human Resource is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."
Demo feedback:  Kristen (GRD) will send her recommendation to add another L3 capability under Campaign Performance Mgmt-ddj

Children.Name: Work Management
Description: <p><span><span>Ability to capture, categorize, organize, prioritize, disseminate, route, assign, administer and analyze a manual or automated activity performed to achieve a purpose or result.</span></span></p>

Comments.Comment: In PI3 workshop, removed verbiage "objects produced by physical or intellectual effort." from definition and used BIZBOK 5.5 p 542 (547 pdf) as basis.
Removed "notification management" per Bill's email on 5/10. He had recommended it be added during PI3 workshop but then changed his mind saying it was redundant.
Examples: job tasks, decisions, published articles.
Work Management incorporates all work movement across a value stream.  The child objects collectively enable the day to day business engagement and interactions.
At Biz Arch Summit Bill indicated Authored Item is the same as Document Management. That term is more in alignment with terminology in use here.
Document is likely misplaced under Work Management. Document is a type of Information (a form factor of information). -WCM

Discussed in workshop with team that schedule is not a level 1 because it exists in the context of other objects, i.e. human resource, asset, plan. It is a time allocation for something. Can be a record of timed events. It is a level two under other capabilities.

Time Processing is a series of clocks that are responsible for managing start and stop points as well as lapsed time. Request/response expiration, time required to respond to a notice, expiration of a license are all examples that can change the state of an object or trigger a value stream or event.

Discussion held Work Mgmt Capabilities and compared to Bizbok 6.5 version. Previous mtg Jeff G, Chris M and Chris T met and proposed refinement with recommendations. Today's meeting with larger team (Cari, Dawn, John S, Mike, Chris T, Chris M) met to align with proposed recommendations to revise and complete our objectives for PI 10 - ddj

Original copy made of Work Mgmt capabilites and placed in 'to be removed folder'. Work Item Mgmt removed and replaced with Work Item Definition and add L3 Work Configuration. Add L2 Work Risk Mgmt. Remove L2 Work Event Mgmt - match work item to event,Remove L2 Decision Mgmt, Remove L2 Document Mgmt, Remove L2 Notification Mgmt - covered under Message Mgmt and remove L2 Time Processing - ddj
Work Item (from BIZBOK 6.5) - A bound task that can be prioritized and delivered to a location or stakeholder.
Example (Work Item) : Drive Car
Task - Measurable amount of work performed to convert inputs into outputs. An assigned work item occurrence.
Example (Task) : Chris drive car from home to work on Wednesday 7/24 at 8:00.
Activity - An orchestration of tasks and capabilities which produce an outcome(s) and achieve value for a value stream stage.
Example (Activity) : Setup Work Areas - All of the work items and capabilities associated with preparing and provisioning the work areas prior to start up of the operation.

Children.Name: Brand Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a brand is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."

Children.Name: Business Entity Management
Children.Description: Ability to create, structure, and govern the legal body or bodies that comprise a single organization, such as a private or public corporation, for-profit or not-for-profit, or government agency.

Comments.Comment: Changed in team workshop. Use definition in reference model on p 573 of BIZBOK.
Propose moving Plan and Strategy L1 capabilities under Business Management.
This capability was cleaned up during PI3 team workshop with Bill U on 4/26 to remove some L2 and L3.
Changed "FedEx" in definition to enterprise and its partners during Manager review of L1. Getting away from use of FedEx in definitions.
BIZBOK: Ability to set strategic direction, generally govern, manage operational execution, and measure performance against plan for the legal entity and its ecosystem.
PP pulled Business Mgmt as 'stretch' objective PI 11. Cari indicated this is more about 'managing the company and organizing the business. -ddj
Updated L1 description to align with Bizbok 7.0 - made copy of original Business Mgmt and placed in 'to be removed folder'.-ddj

PI 11 Sprint 4 demo:  PP and RD presented the first draft and agreement from COP team to move forward with change to L1 as Business 'Entity' Mgmt and further define L3s with examples. Here are the noted changes:
Renamed L1 to Business Entity Mgmt - aligned description to Bizbok 7.0
Added L3 Business Entity Structure - under Definition
Added L3 Business Entity Establishment - under Definition
Added L2 Business Entity Risk Mgmt (pattern)
Removed L2 Business Visualization - covered under Analytics
Removed L2 Business Solution - covered under Business Entity Structure

Removed L2 Capability Mgmt and L2 Value Stream Mgmt - Bus Arch is an analytic framework driving design decisions based on the analytics. (should not be called separately, consider other key business components such as QDM, SAFE, etc) - ddj

SME Jakub Novak (Corp Development & Integration) stated Business Entity looks at 3 areas: Information Security, Legal Compliance/Regulatory and Financial Controls.  Noted additional examples in the capabilities from SME input.  Jakub asked where is the reporting structure (e.g. VP, EVP) covered? - it is part of Bus Entity Structure capability. SME also asked where would we account for the daily execution of running the business?

CB, JS, CT, CM, AG ,BF, DJ : follow-up discussion from RPE 12 demo of Business Entity to determine where does the Bus Arch Capability for modeling solutions belong?  Agreement to add 'L2 Visualization' from the Business Archived folder and 'L3 Current State' and 'L3 Target State'. The rationale is this capability does not contain a 'design or conceptualization' capability under Definition. Therefore, the Visualization capability is needed to close the gap to represent the work of Business Architecture. Solution is a information concept and we do not need to represent it as a capability. Team to review the Capability Map to identify if the 'Visualization' capability is needed when no Design or Conceptualization capability exists which may include visualization. Visualization includes models (BPM, Data, etc), graphs, charts or any other visual representations.

Rationale for adding Business Entity Management "Because business architecture is an abstraction of a business, the capability(s) you seek is under Business Entity Management (there is no Business Management in the ref models now). For example, Business Entity Visualization (proposed but not in model today) would be the L2 capability. This capability is a what and the specifics (org mapping, capability mapping, etc.) would be how (not what) something is done." - Bill Ulrich. CT

Children.Name: Initiative Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well an Initiative is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."

Attributes.AttributeValue: (e.g. return on investment (ROI) measurement, key performance indicators (KPI) measurement, cost, defect, and milestone monitoring etc)

SME Abhijeet Bhat indicated the Capability model reviewed aligns with his area responsibilities which include Corp Strategy 2 types: Annual corp projects very rapid 4-6 months to develop annually and Adhoc projects 3-4 weeks on every project. Look at new market analysis. 4 step process: 1)Research to address the business problem, customer needs, opportunities/challenges, data points, product info, etc. 2)Define scope from solution perspective 3) Build strategy -define priority, data analysis, what if scenarios, socialize with business leaders for alignment 4)Deliver recommendation-to achieve consensus on a fact basis for different OPCOs (Express, GRD, etc).

SME Jack Fong area responsible for Strategy Planning: work with executive level VP and above(e.g. Rob Carter), projects span 2-3 years out such as Options Grid and MYP, determine how to sequence products and organize work at a higher level, determine the T-shirt sizing and value how it impacts the ECF, encourage collaboration among teams (Planner-Jack team, PMO-Lisa Gwatney team, Architecture-John Suzanne team), work with Nate Babcock to funnel demand. To view the Multi-Year Planning process flow, enter keyword 'MYP' - ddj

SME Nate Babcock (Strategic Planning GPE) reviewed the Express Stair-Step Strategic Planning Diagram and indicated it is not a MVP. It outlines how we deliver solutions at a high level. Vision is the future state executives envision. Goal is directional in desire to grow revenue. Objective is specific in how to grow it. A single strategy may have multiple goals. Objectives should be 'value focused'. Need to identify gaps. Actions are mapped to Value Stream Stages and Business Capabilities. Capabilities are mapped to existing applications and services. Business Solution is the target state gap analysis matched to the strategy.

Comments.Comment: L1 definition reviewed with ART members on 3/10/17 in workshop
Examples include contracts, SLAs, Master Service Agreement, contract of carriage, SOW, agreements between FX and independent contractors, and FX and USPS.

( ! ) Having the term "legally" in our definition for Agreement narrows and unduly constrains what types of things can be subtypes of Agreement. For example, some SLAs are legally binding and some are not. Does that mean that an SLA is or is not an Agreement? From general vernacular, Agreement is defined as "a binding arrangement, understanding or obligation between two or more entities." (no "legally")  Contract is defined as "a legaly binding agreement". These definitions are not only more aligned with generally accepted semantics, but also much better enable capability and business object decomposition. -WCM

Children.Name: Asset Management
Children.Description: The ability to acquire, deploy, maintain, use, analyze, and retire tangible or intangible resources that the business owns, manages, or leases to produce value.
R.StakeholderEnablesCapRelationship: Fleet Maintenance Innovation, Process, and Compliance

Comments.Comment: L1 definition reviewed with ART members on 3/10/17 in workshop
Examples removed from definition during 3/31 workshop by team: planes, trucks, office equipment, ULDs, devices, trailers, conveyors, hardware, software, facilities, land, equipment etc

Chris M proposed to break out into categories: property, equipment, facility, software rather than have one broad category. Group (LA, CB, MP, CT) decided to keep as "asset" for now rather than have multiple L1 capabilities as they are very similar. If they differentiate at lower levels, we can identify those later. Chris said it can work that way, but was concerned it is too broad.
Does NOT include facility (separate capability).
Examples: Includes conveyors. Conveyors are aircraft, locomotive with cars, tractor with trailer(s), van, etc
Removed "things" from definition and kept objects during manager review.

The term "asset" is typically an accounting designation of something's ascribed value within a context such as a balance sheet. Almost anything, tangible or intangible, may be designated as an asset (or liability) depending upon context, age, condition, etc. Deviating our definition to essentially mean "stuff" (or, "all stuff not explicitly otherwise defined") renders the concept so broad as to be useless from an information and capability mapping perspective. Core business capabilities, even for somewhat broader concepts, should be explicitly defined and represented in the map. We do not need and should not attempt to define a "catch all" capability or information concept. Doing so (for Asset) has already resulted in lack of rigor and ambiguity when decomposing lower level capabilities or information concepts. It is perfectly fine to represent this concept in a Value Stream, but "Asset Management" is not an L1 business capability. Such a capability may exist as a lower level capability under Finance, Accounting or the like. -WCM
Carolyn Clements and Stacey Bradley were the SMEs for this and they are from Capital Planning / Asset Management

During a workshop on 10/15, the team came to an agreement that asset management would be kept, rather than breaking it into categories. The definition was refined. Conveyor Management was moved to "to be removed" and archived. Facility Management stays separate for now.

Children.Name: Asset Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well an Asset is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."

Children.Name: Claim Subrogation
Children.Description: Ability to pursue recoveries from other parties associated with a claim.

Comments.Comment: Added by CB from BIZBOK p 584.
SMEs: Monica McClure, Dawn Eberle, Charmaine Santarelli (FCA Recovery) - for Subrogation Mgmt Capability - ddj
o	Ensure money is received
1.	Receive a report of accident - side swipe
2.	Determine if subrogation claim
3.	Enter into database (all claim information)
4.	Identify the type (Vehicle MX, Cargo, Environmental, Property) to determine who will research further
5.	If a Fire send to Forrest Luster with details of trailer incident number and loading tracking number (Customer has 9 months to file a claim)
6.	Trailer fire is 80K huge dollar loss - track all expenses
7.	Police report - list contact and insurance information
8.	FedEx call the insurance company to initiate a claim
9.	We send letter to the insurance company
10.	We follow up every 30 days for status
11.	We negotiate with insurance company
12.	If a 70k loss, we may only receive 10k (due to insurance policy limits)
•	36% claims (Monica/Dawn) processed for damage to FedEx property
•	Claims are categorized by Cargo, Environmental spills, Facilities, Vehicle Maintenance, Trailer damage
o	Need data from accident to our property or 3rd party property and track in the database
o	Need capabilities to extract the data
o	Collaboration and cross functions involved (Safety, Field, Risk Mgmt) to support the police report and photos
o	Professional resources (Monica/Dawn) needed to understand and fact find to obtain pertinent information
o	Identify what expenses are incurred and databases (e.g. Index models, PeopleSoft) needed to gather and calculate the information

Children.Name: Conveyor Management
Children.Description: The ability to design, procure, maintain, and dispose of any variety of an apparatus, whether human-piloted or by robot process automation that has the ability to transport people, animals, goods, assets, or other physical items.

Comments.Comment: Conveyor Mgmt capabilities defined by the Kanban Team (CT, CM, Agila, Laura, Dawn) per the Ground Workshop held in PITT facilitated by Bill Ulrich (Chris T and Chris M in attendance) Conveyor Mgmt L1 is now included in Bizbok 7.5 Guild Transportation Reference Model - ddj
Conveyor definition updated in the Information: Conveyor - An apparatus that has the ability to transport people, animals, goods, assets, or other physical items.

It was suggested by Bill Ulrich and agreed upon by the Business Architecture Community as a whole to call out conveyor management as an L1 capability. There was a concern brought out that if we break conveyor out of Asset Management, then we might as well break out all the various types of assets as L1's (about 6 give or take) and get rid of Asset Management. However, Bill explained that is not necessary and that it's a bad idea to deprecate Asset Management from the capability map. The reason for breaking out conveyor is because we are a Transportation Company and Conveyor Management is therefore a core capability. We agreed that Conveyor Management is a core capability and plays into our strategy and is key to gaining a competitive advantage in the transportation industry. Conveyor Management is especially important when considering the role  automated conveyors such as drones and robots play in our current and future business/operational solutions. CT

We updated the Conveyor Business Object in the Information map to be more accurate. This definition was partly inspired by the guild definition of conveyor. Conveyor Business Object Definition - An apparatus that has the ability to transport people, animals, goods, assets, or other physical items. CT
Approved in the Manager Review held on 12/11/2019. Changing Status to Approved. CT
Approved in the MD Review held on 12/19/2019. Changing status to Published. CT

Children.Name: Conveyor Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a conveyor is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Performance is not the same as analytics. CT I asked Bill Ulrich to explain the difference and he wrote: "Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap." - Bill Ulrich.

Performance definition - Performance - The result and effectiveness of an action or process of carrying out or accomplishing an action, task, or function according to specification or objective levels determined by a plan, design, directive, etc. - BOM (The definition we have in the Business Object Model) CT

Children.Name: Facility Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a Facility is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."

Children.Name: Handling Unit Management
Children.Description: The ability to establish, use, sustain, distribute and analyze tangible units/items configured and identified for movement through the transportation network.

Comments.Comment: P&D vehicles are also Handling Units
The definition of Handling Unit was derived from Biz Dictionary.com; international shipment definition stuff (see Chris marsh).
At the lowest level, Handling Units are the smallest  item that can be managed by FedEx.  FedEx can only accept shipment units that are in the form of handling units
These are generally conveyance items; and can be assets;
This contains sub-capabilities related to managing movement of Handling Unit
Handling Units can be hierarchical (Bags in Headload in trailers on a train; etc…);  Handling Units can be nested and de-nested;  (i.e., consolidated)
Handling Units can be physical assets

FXE Examples from Jeff - Dell Computers with Merge-In-Transit goals.  Components from different locations & shippers; the bundled keyboards constitute 'handling units' from a fedex perspective (?); even though they were many different shipments from a customer perspective.
Thinking of SmartPost consolidations; the delivery of a palletized set of shipments to a DDU constitutes a  Handling Unit
For FXF, Handling Units are pallets that are grouped together into shipments for a BOL.  Jackie was in attendance and supported this.
Re-added in a meeting on 1/25/17 (CT, CM, MP, JG, CB)

Instances: Handling units are packages, carton, pallet, skid, or other bundled or unitized cargo that is individually identified and independently distributed or transported.  It may be a document or standard form factor packaging, consolidate other handling units or contents, or be a large item provided by a customer such as a refrigerator, auto part, pallet, etc.  This also includes various assets such as ULDs, Vessels, Trailers, and other items to be determined.
Handling units are things that can be transported.
Validation Team recommended some examples be added.
Should there be handling unit inventory management?

Comments.Comment: Notes from Ground Meeting: Initial discussion is that Geography Management should be wrapped up within the Network Management capability.

Beth Canale - Sales Territories (Sales and Customer alignments sometimes associated with geographical boundries), Tech Connect - Field Service "coverage" assignments tied to mix of Geographical and Geopolitical type data , Customer Consultants (used to be referred to as CIC's are a hybrid of Sales and Tech Support) also has coverage tied to to mix of Geographical and Geopolitical type data, Geopolitical data outside of just city/state/region, etc.. type consideration, timezones and holidays are factored in

Much discussion about geography - regardless of how / where this capability lives, we discussed how service areas might be a proxy / abstraction of a station node.  Jeff maintains that the station service area is itself a node, and connections between stations and service areas are arcs, and the connections can then enable multiple connections.  Definitions of allowable transit must be on the arcs, not on the nodes.
Cari had info from a reference model that showed these L2 capabilities - Geographic definition, Geographic administration, Geographic relationship / hierarchical administration.
At the end of the day, I don't think we're resolved that this is a level one, but don't think we can solve it now.
Removed following from definition "that are used to define service offerings, regulatory constraints, territories, etc. that support operations." during team workshop.
Reviewed during team workshop with Whynde K and this is accepted as a level 1. (Maps are not and were removed).

Examples: external such as postal codes, cities, countries and regions, and internal such as service areas, sales regions, territories, staging areas, load positions on a truck or aircraft, and geofences.

Children.Name: Network Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a Network is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."

Children.R.GapConsidersElementRelationship: [Theme.GapAnalysis]|[EXAMPLE.GapAnalysis]|EXAMPLE - Initiative: Example Initiative A|(Example) Express - ValueStage: Execute Operation - Plan Operation|(Example) Express - Activity: Execute Operation - Plan Operation - Create Trip Plan

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."
Demo feedback:  Kristen (GRD) will send her recommendation to add another L3 capability under Campaign Performance Mgmt-ddj

Comments.Comment: Notes from Ground Meeting: After Inventory Management discussion, we went to the order management.   Jeff indicated that there four types of Order Management types:  Demand Orders; Supply Orders; Shipment Orders; Purchase Orders.
These seem to be somewhat standard types of orders .  Given where FedEx wants to get to (supply Chain, Fulfillment, etc.), it probably makes sense to  reflect mature order management capabilities.
IF we head down this path, do we think that Inventory Management becomes part of Order Management?  (I think yes….)

Carrie noted that from the BizBOK perspective, decomposing capabilities should be around the same business object.  Otherwise, they are different capabilities.  This argues that Inventory management and order management are different capabilities.
Removed "by a customer" from the definition during team workshop as it could be internal. Also removed services and replaced with "assets".
Example: sales order (product leaving warehouse), purchase order (product coming into warehouse), service order (copies, binding)

Children.Name: Partner Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a partner is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."
Demo feedback:  Kristen (GRD) will send her recommendation to add another L3 capability under Campaign Performance Mgmt-ddj

Comments.Comment: I think originally we thought that this might be a duplicate of shipment to shipment matching.  However, upon thinking it through, I believe that we need it for multi-piece shipments:

Multiple-Piece Shipment: For FedEx Express and FedEx Ground package services, you can ship multiple piece as a multiple-piece shipment if the pieces: 1) use the same service, bill-to instructions, packaging type and delivery instructions (including FedEx Delivery Signature Options, collect on delivery, FedEx Express Saturday pickup or delivery, Hold at FedEx Location, or FedEx Home Delivery convenient delivery options); 2) move together on the same day from one sender to one recipient; and 3) meet all size, weight and acceptance guidelines for the selected service. Individual packages in a multiple-piece shipment may have different

weights, dimensions and declared value. Within the U.S. only, individual packages in a multiple-piece shipment processed using FedEx electronic shipping solutions may contain different designations of dangerous goods (for FedEx Express) or hazardous materials

(for FedEx Ground). All labeling requirements, guidelines and restrictions apply. Each individual piece or single handling unit must have an address label showing complete sender and recipient addresses. Multiple-piece shipments tendered as express freight must be palletized, stackable, forkliftable, banded and shrinkwrapped to form single handling units. Once a multiple-piece shipment tendered via a U.S. package service reaches a total

shipment weight of 100 lbs. for FedEx Express (200 lbs. for FedEx Express Saver) or 200 lbs. for FedEx Ground (with contract-only FedEx Ground Multiweight rates), it is rated based on price per package and price per total shipment weight. You are billed the lower of the two rates. For FedEx Express, a 15-lb. average minimum package weight for the shipment applies. For FedEx Ground, an average minimum package weight for the shipment applies and varies by contract. FedEx Express international multiple-piece

shipments are billed based on total shipment weight. FedEx One Rate multiple-piece shipments are not eligible for FedEx Express Multiweight pricing. All FedEx electronic shipping solutions can create shipping labels for FedEx Express and

FedEx Ground multiple-piece shipments within the U.S., and will place a master tracking number and package-count sequence and total on each label. A FedEx Express Package US Airbill or FedEx Express Freight US Airbill can accept up to 999 pieces as a multiplepiece shipment (except for shipments in FedEx® Envelope or FedEx 10kg Box and FedEx
25kg Box packaging).  FedEx 2016 Service Guide, p. 125.
A Handling Unit that is part of a Shipment is a Shipment Unit. -WCM

Attributes.AttributeValue: (i.e. a multi-piece shipment, this could be a one to one or a one to many relationship).

Children.Name: Trip Performance Management
Children.Description: Ability to determine how well a Trip is meeting specification and objective levels, or delivering against plan.

Comments.Comment: Response below from Bill Ulrich regarding Performance Mgmt is a valid capability and does not overlap with Analytics (email titled 'Capability Pattern dated 9/11/19). - ddj

"Performance Management - this is not just a set of metrics. First, I have to be able to set a standard and then measure performance against that standard. This differs by object, which makes the capability unique not only in general but specifically based on business object. Take an human resource evaluator; they can tell you how to do Human (Resource) Performance Measurement. They or someone sets goals or standards that should be achieved; the human is then objectively or subjectively compared to those standards; or sometimes, the boss just says “great job” - all of this is under the performance capability. Now do this for a network - a very different story but you still set and assess how the object is performing against a threshold. Repeat this thinking now for a partner, or a conveyor, etc. Go tell the evaluators that have these capabilities that they can be replaced by a spreadsheet. The point here is you may or may not use analytics to represent the results (either way) but setting and assessing against benchmarks are very real capabilities, and analytics may not come into play. There is no overlap."
Demo feedback:  Kristen (GRD) will send her recommendation to add another L3 capability under Campaign Performance Mgmt-ddj

Children.Name: Trip Performance Threshold Setting
Children.Description: Ability to determine acceptable or unacceptable levels of performance for a Trip.

Attributes.AttributeValue: e.g. Trip must include at least 10 waypoints.

Children.Name: Trip Performance Threshold Measurement
Children.Description: Ability to determine if a Trip is exceeding or falling short of an acceptable threshold of performance.

Attributes.AttributeValue: e.g. Track the number of waypoints a Trip has included.

Children.Name: Trip Performance Constraints Determination
Children.Description: Ability to assess what is causing an Trip to under perform.

Attributes.AttributeValue: e.g. The Trip is under performing due to Itinerary and waypoint errors.

Children.Name: Trip Access Management
Children.Description: Ability to establish, control, restrict, and administer rights to view, use, or change a Trip in a variety of contexts.

Children.Name: Trip Access Constraints Definition
Children.Description: Ability to define and impose limitations of access rights to a given Trip or set of Trips.

Attributes.AttributeValue: Ex: A manager is given the ability or right to view or change trip information

Children.Name: Trip Access Constraints Interpretation
Children.Description: Ability to understand imposed access rights limitations for a given Trip or set of Trips.

Attributes.AttributeValue: Ex: Based on a a FXE operations agent's EID, the system identifies access rights to reroute shipment trips to/from IND due to severe weather. Or, based on permissions defined, a rail yard is allowed to update FedEx trip information when conveyors or containers arrive at the yard.

Children.Name: Trip Access Enforcement
Children.Description: Ability to ensure that access rights are granted where constraints are not appropriate and to prevent access where constraints are in place to prevent access.

Attributes.AttributeValue: Ex: System grants access to a customer service agent to view a shipment trip itinerary but not change it.
